# Cursor AI Rules

## Code Style and Quality

- Write clean, readable, and maintainable code
- Follow language-specific best practices and conventions
- Use consistent naming conventions throughout the codebase
- Keep functions small and focused on a single responsibility
- Add comments only when the code's intent isn't self-evident

## Security Practices

- Never include API keys, passwords, or secrets in code
- Validate and sanitize all user inputs
- Use parameterized queries for database operations
- Follow OWASP security guidelines
- Keep dependencies updated and check for vulnerabilities

## Testing

- Write tests for critical functionality
- Test edge cases and error conditions
- Ensure tests are independent and repeatable
- Keep test coverage at reasonable levels

## Documentation

- Update README files when adding new features
- Document complex algorithms and business logic
- Use clear docstrings/JSDoc for public APIs
- Keep documentation in sync with code changes

## Git Practices

- Write clear, descriptive commit messages
- Keep commits atomic and focused
- Create feature branches for new work
- Squash commits before merging when appropriate

## AI Assistance Guidelines

- Prefer editing existing files over creating new ones
- Don't add unnecessary abstractions or over-engineer solutions
- Only add error handling for realistic failure scenarios
- Avoid adding features beyond what was requested
- Trust framework and library guarantees
- Delete unused code completely rather than commenting it out
